        "$70$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "The captain is already on the team, so only $3$ more players must be chosen from the remaining $8$. Since a team is unordered, the count is $\\binom{8}{3} = \\dfrac{8 \\times 7 \\times 6}{3 \\times 2 \\times 1} = 56$. The answer $126 = \\binom{9}{4}$ ignores the captain restriction and chooses all four freely, while $70 = \\binom{8}{4}$ keeps the right pool of $8$ but the wrong number to pick. The trap is not reducing both counts after fixing the captain: include him for free and choose only $3$ from the other $8$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Rosen, Discrete Mathematics and Its Applications"
    },
    {
      "id": "discrete-mathematics-combinatorics-023",
      "stem": "How many distinct arrangements of the letters of the word $\\text{LEVEL}$ begin and end with the letter $\\text{L}$?",
      "options": [
        "$6$",
        "$3$",
        "$12$",
        "$2$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "The word $\\text{LEVEL}$ has letters L, E, V, E, L: two L's, two E's, and one V. Placing an L at each end uses up both L's, and the two middle-end positions are now fixed. The three interior slots must be filled with E, V, E, which has $\\dfrac{3!}{2!} = 3$ arrangements because the two E's repeat. So the answer is $3$. The count $6 = 3!$ forgets that the two interior E's are identical, and $12$ double counts by also swapping the two fixed L's. The trap is treating the repeated E's (and L's) as distinct: identical letters never create new arrangements.",
      "difficulty": "stretch",
      "source": "in the style of Epp, Discrete Mathematics with Applications"
    },
    {
      "id": "discrete-mathematics-combinatorics-024",
      "stem": "A drawer contains socks of $4$ colours, mixed together in the dark. What is the least number of socks one must pull out to be certain of getting at least one matching pair (two socks of the same colour)?",
      "options": [
        "$4$",
        "$8$",
        "$2$",
        "$5$"
