      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "The $4$ colours act as pigeonholes. Pulling $4$ socks could give one of each colour with no pair, so $4$ is not yet safe. The $5$th sock must repeat a colour already drawn, guaranteeing a matching pair. By the pigeonhole principle the threshold is $4 + 1 = 5$. The answer $4$ stops at the number of colours, and $8$ assumes you need two of every colour. The trap is forgetting the extra item: to force a repeat you need one more than the number of categories, not the number of categories itself.",
      "difficulty": "stretch",
      "source": "in the style of Rosen, Discrete Mathematics and Its Applications"
    },
    {
      "id": "discrete-mathematics-combinatorics-025",
      "stem": "A commercial vehicle plate has the form $\\text{AS}$, then $4$ digits, then $1$ letter, where the letter may be any of $\\text{A}$ to $\\text{Z}$ except it may not be a vowel (A, E, I, O, U). Digits run $0$ to $9$ with repetition allowed. How many such plates are possible?",
      "options": [
